Topic — The Impact of AI on Employment

Slide 2 — Why This Question Matters
Generative AI now automates tasks once considered safe.
This creates real fear of mass job loss.
Task automation does not equal job elimination.
Early evidence since ChatGPT points to stability, not collapse.

Slide 3 — The “AI Apocalypse” View
AI leaders like Sam Altman warn of large‑scale job replacement.
Customer support is a clear early target.
Salesforce cutting thousands of support roles shows why these fears feel credible.

Slide 4 — AI Exposure Across the Labor Market
AI exposure is spread across jobs, not universal.
ILO data shows a spectrum of exposure levels.
Most jobs sit in the middle — not fully safe, not fully doomed.
Even high‑exposure jobs contain mixed tasks.

Slide 5 — Not All Jobs Face the Same Risk
Software developers face higher exposure but high task variety.
Physical, hands‑on jobs remain far less exposed.
Exposure means change, not guaranteed replacement.

Slide 6 — No Jobs Apocalypse — For Now
Brookings researchers tested whether AI is eliminating jobs at scale.
If it were, we would see fewer workers in high‑exposure occupations.
Instead, employment shares have stayed remarkably stable.
AI is reshaping work, not wiping it out.

Slide 7 — Two Caveats
Stability today doesn’t guarantee stability forever.
Past technologies reshaped work slowly.
Early‑career workers may already be more vulnerable.
No apocalypse yet does not mean no future risk.

Slide 8 — Worst‑Case Scenario: Can Workers Adapt?
About 37 million workers face high AI exposure.
Most also have strong adaptive capacity.
Only about 4% face both high exposure and low adaptability.
Vulnerability is real, but limited and concentrated.

Slide 9 — What This Means for CS Students
Parts of programming are automatable.
Judgment, design, debugging, and communication still matter.
Near‑term impact is job redesign, not disappearance.
Learning to use AI tools is essential.

Slide 10 — Conclusion
AI is already affecting some jobs.
Research shows no broad labor‑market collapse so far.
Future disruption is possible, especially for certain groups.
The right response is adaptation, not panic.

Slide 11 — Sources
These conclusions are based on ILO data, Brookings research, and industry reporting.
